column15: Misconceptions with the coronary circulation. You are correct that there is a coronary artery but there are 2 branches of it which you do not highlight nor do you describe which specific chambers of the heart each branch supplies blood to. You also are also incorrect about how the blood from the coronary circulation re-enters the regular circulatory system to be re-oxygenated (it does not re-enter in the vena cava). Please review the recorded lecture from 9/15 (I believe it is around minute 38) to refresh this concept then revise your video and resubmit.

column15: Okay there is a LOT going on in this video and I honestly am not sure what token you are wanting to submit this under because you literally touch on all of them in some way BUT since you have this labeled as an FBD DOK-3 I will be reviewing on only that portion of this video while making comments on the rest...First congrats on the abstract submission BUT I would like you to clarify if you submitted different abstracts to both RMBS and NCUR. Conferences do not allow multiple submissions of the same abstract and if this was done one of them must be withdrawn (you cannot publish something twice). If the abstracts contained different aspects of your experiment and are focusing on differences in data collection/analysis that is okay but submitting an identical abstract is not. Abstract submissions are for DOK-4 tokens as they show your impact so please make these separate tokens. Next thank you for discussing your contributions specifically with the equation work. For DOK-3 tokens we are wanting you to apply your knowledge of a pillar and your individual work contributions to your project note that this does NOT have to be done for all the pillars just some of the pillars. Now for discussion of your pillars. FBD: since I will be reviewing based on this portion of your video I will go into detail. Your FBD portion to me was more of a connection rather than an application because you merely relate where the disease is located and do not make a clear application to the project with it. Yes there is a disease that is associated with these areas that is clear but how does this effect your contributions to the projects experimental set up? How has your understanding of the pillar benefited your PM2.5 experimental design? These are questions that if answer could push this from DOK-2 to DOK-3 for me. I really liked the connection you made in the R&C pillar you should definitely make a DOK-2 token for that.

column15: Incorrect statements in the video. Resistance varies independent of pressure. Equations for resistance may include pressure but this should not be misunderstood to say that a change in pressure CAUSES a change in resistance. The equation simply means that resistance can be calculated if the flow rate and pressure differential are known. Addison's disease relates to a cortisol deficiency. Cortisol is a muscle stimulant and the heart is a muscle. A deficiency in heart stimulation leads to reduced heart rate and reduced blood flow (Q). It is the reduced Q (and constant R) that leads to reduced P (blood pressure). It is also inappropriate to infer any change in compliance/elastance in response to reduced Q and P. Please revise and resubmit with a focus on how the FLOW past your sensor will go DOWN when blood pressure goes DOWN due to Addison's disease.

column15: Good connections to your project. I would like to highlight that when you are discussing PV loops and comparing the v-fib to "infinite resistance" that it is only partially correct. It is true that cases of v-fib and infinite resistance both have low/no blood flow into the arterial system BUT the key difference is WHY the flow of blood is low or not flowing at all. In case of infinite resistance the assumption is a healthy heart would create more pressure due to an increased resistance. In the case of v-fib the heart is not pumping blood at all (as you state in your video). So v-fib is different than the infinite resistance example because there is low/no blood flow AND low pressure.

column15: Connection made to project. I would like to highlight that when you are comparing fibrillation to "infinite resistance" that it is only partially correct. It is true that cases of fibrillation and infinite resistance both have low/no blood flow into the arterial system BUT the key difference is WHY the flow of blood is low or not flowing at all. In case of infinite resistance the assumption is a healthy heart would create more pressure due to an increased resistance. In the case of fibrillation the heart is not pumping blood at all so it is different than the infinite resistance example because there is low/no blood flow AND low pressure.

column15: There are good connections to your project within this video however there are also some conceptual errors. You met the criteria for DOK2 reasoning (applying knowledge skills and reasoning to your project) but I would revisit the concept of diodes and how that correlates to the PV loop.Good connections to your project. I would like to highlight that when you are discussing PV loops and comparing the v-fib to "infinite resistance" that it is only partially correct. It is true that cases of v-fib and infinite resistance both have low/no blood flow into the arterial system BUT the key difference is WHY the flow of blood is low or not flowing at all. In case of infinite resistance the assumption is a healthy heart would create more pressure due to an increased resistance. In the case of v-fib the heart is not pumping blood at all (as you state in your video). So v-fib is different than the infinite resistance example because there is low/no blood flow AND low pressure.Good start: "Qin is zero AoP will drop" But then you go to the PV loop and point to the red line. This line represents the HIGHEST pressure line on the graph but you just said that AoP (Aortic Pressure) was dropping! This indicates a misunderstanding of the mathematical relationship (ohm's law for the heart). Flow ~

column15: Token is for DOK-3 of the ECG pillar. Contribution was using HFSS to design an antenna. Lacks personal discussion of how these contributions along with your knowledge of ECG was useful towards project development. HOWEVER in the paper there is discussion of complications with leads for defibrillators "The most recent implantable cardioverter defibrillator (ICD) designs utilize leads to both read electrical activity in the heart and deliver defibrillation when necessary. The problem is the leads that are inserted into the heart often need to be replaced due to infection lead fracture or displacement and a blockage of vein pathways all of which can cause major complications." and there is mention of their design being a "viable approach to leadless defibrillation"... "We do believe that this is a viable approach to leadless defibrillation but that we need to continue to adjust the design in order to meet the requirements to defibrillate." which is stated without (I assume) expert revision. My issue is I am not sure who wrote what parts of the paper...The proof of submission is an email confirmation of submission not sure if this is accepted or not yet. Idk I would like to know other's opinions as well. I am declining it as a DOK3 ECG token specifically due to the fact that all of the application evidence (if that even counts) is in a paper that lacks information about who wrote what parts. column15: As in your DOK1 token on PV Loops you have some incorrect statements about Starling's Law. The connections from your project to the pillar of PV Loops/ Time Domain is solid but the misunderstanding of the material itself why this token cannot be passed.	Starling's law of the heart applies to a healthy heart being stretched a little extra. CHF involves abnormal hearts diastolic CHF has standard ESV but reduced EDV (reduced SV) systolic CHF has increased EDV and (even more) increase to ESV In both cases Stroke Volume is less than for a normal heart. "unable to keep up with extra work over a long period of time" leads to... heart palpitations? how about "leads to hypertrophy"

column15: Blood pressure can be a cause of CHF due to the extra exertion the heart must perform in order to circulate blood. I agree with the previous instructor review: "poor understanding of both the project (CHF) and the underlying DOK-1 concept. In CHF blood pressure increases BECAUSE the resistance increases. (heart is working to maintain average flow Q into larger resistance). 1:30 "the elasticity or compliance may actually be lowered" The term is elastance (not elasticity). Elastance and compliance are opposites of one another - if one is lowered the other goes up. 1:40 "of certain arteries or veins" veins always have low elastance

column15: Great work on the team. However I could not fully grasp how you used or applied FBD to your project. Yes your research is vital and important to take the idea and bring it to market. You mentioned briefly what the "business" process would be but why is this important to the group? What are the pros and cons of bringing the idea to market? What other "high impact" pathways are possible for this group? Overall the token seemed a bit too shallow for me to consider it to be a DOK-4 for this Cardiovascular Engineering course. One great way to make a deeper application and possibly a DOK-4 level token is to talk about WHY this needs FDA approval. Yes you'll be dealing with the cardiovascular system and it's easy to identify the need for "some" FDA approval but what are the specifics? What does the CP Model analyze that requires it to go through such rigorous regulation? Has there been any competitive product? Are there different types of FDA regulations for diagnostic / modeling software? Is the plan to embed the software on a chip (hardware) and if so are there additional regulations? Is this going to be used only in the hospital and clinical settings? What about the clinical trial process and regulatory pathways for clinical trials? Responses to these questions I would hope to see in a DOK-4 token from a team member who wants to focus on regulatory instead of the software/model development which is very important!
